{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511043"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11694"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.14,0.15,0.06,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1635"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7864"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man is delivered to the Emergency Department after falling off the roof and hitting his chest. He is able to recall what happened, but feels breathless and finds it painful to speak or take a deep breath. On examination his airway is clear, his blood pressure is 80/45mmHg, pulse 120/min, oxygen saturation 97% on room air, respiratory rate 18. His trachea is in the midline and his neck veins are distended. Widespread subcutaneous crepitus can be palpated over the chest wall, making a full cardiorespiratory auscultation difficult, however he appears to have equal air entry bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this patient that would necessitate urgent intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flail chest segment","Bilateral pneumothoraces","Tension pneumothorax","Rupture of the diaphragm","Cardiac tamponade"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient may have sustained several chest/intrathoracic injuries given the mechanism of injury. The findings of crepitus is indicative of air in the subcutaneous tissues, which is likely associated with the presence of rib fractures and possible pneumothorax. Whilst a pneumothorax may require some form of intervention, the more worrying diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecardiac tamponade. \u003C/strong\u003EThis patient is hypotensive and has distended neck veins, which are two of the three components of Becks\u0027 Triad. The third sign is diminished heart sounds, however this sign cannot determined due to the nature of the patient\u0027s injury. Additionally, the vital signs indicate that the patient is haemodynamically unstable, necessitating urgent management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther signs of cardiac tamponade include tachycardia (which is present in this patient) and pulsus paradoxus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eflail chest\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as segmental (fractured in at least 2 places) fractures of 3 or more contiguous ribs resulting in paradoxical movement of the chest wall during respiration. The most common aetiology is trauma to the chest, which is consistent with the history, and is often associated with pain on deep inspiration. However, without visualising the paradoxical movement of the chest wall or imaging confirming the fractures, this diagnosis is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral pneumothoraces \u003C/strong\u003Eare quite rare, though can be precipitated by chest wall trauma, and so should be considered. However, in such a situation there would be severe dyspnoea, respiratory distress and hypoxia. On examination you would expect to find reduced air entry bilaterally,  reduced chest wall movement with respiration and hyper-resonance on percussion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of the diaphragm \u003C/strong\u003Eand similar injuries are quite uncommon and typically occur in the setting of severe trauma, such as motor vehicle accidents. Depending on the severity, patients may be asymptomatic or in more severe cases they could have respiratory distress, including ipsilateral reduced breath sounds and tracheal deviation. Considering the nature of the trauma, this diagnosis is unlikely, though should be investigated thoroughly as to not be missed as herniation and subsequent strangulation of abdominal contents could occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension pneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E is an emergency and must be ruled out quickly. Hypotension, tachycardia and chest pain can all be suggestive of a tension pneumothorax. The most reassuring sign in this patient is the midline trachea - in a tension pneumothorax (of large enough size) there would be tracheal shift to the side opposite the pneumothorax. Whilst this could definitely occur in this patient, it is not currently the biggest concern, though monitoring of the patient should continue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beck\u0027s Triad for cardiac tamponade consists of hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and elevated JVP.","Tension pneumothorax and cardiac tamponade require emergency management."],"references":["Adler Y, Charron P, Imazio M, et al; ESC Scientific Document Group. 2015 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of pericardial diseases: The Task Force for the Diagnosis and Management of Pericardial Diseases of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC)Endorsed by: The European Association for Cardio-Thoracic Surgery (EACTS). Eur Heart J. 2015;36(42):2921-2964. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26320112/","Maskell N. British thoracic society pleural disease guidelines-2010 update. Thorax. 2010 Aug 1;65(8):667-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20685739/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11694"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T18:39:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T18:39:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4309"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113111"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i